05901nam a22008415i 9780823292547DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232925477 a10.1515/97808232925472doi  a(DE-B1597)566016  a(OCoLC)1306541727  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLCO0100002bisacsh00aScrolls of Love :bRuth and the Song of Songs /ced. by Peter S. Hawkins, Lesleigh Cushing Stahlberg. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b16 Illustrations, black and white  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aScrolls of Love is a book of unions. Edited by a Jew and a Christian who are united by a shared passion for the Bible and a common literary hermeneutic, it joins two biblical scrolls and gathers around them a diverse community of interpreters. It brings together Ruth and the Song of Songs, two seemingly disparate texts of the Hebrew Bible, and reads them through a number of the methodological and theological perspectives. Respectful of traditional biblical scholarship, the collection of essays moves beyond it; alert to contemporary trends, the volume returns venerable interpretive tradition to center stage. Most significantly, it is interfaith. Despite the fact that Jews and Christians share a common text in the Hebrew Scripture, the two communities have read their Bibles in isolation from one another, in ignorance of the richness of the other's traditions of reading. Scrolls of Love brings the two traditions into dialogue, enriching established modes of interpretation with unconventional ones. The result is a volume that sets rabbinic, patristic, and medieval readings alongside feminist, psychoanalytic, and autobiographical ones, combining historical, literary, and textual criticism with a variety of artistic reinterpretations—wood cuts and paper cuts, poetry and fiction. Some of the works are scholarly, with the requisite footnotes to draw readers to further inquiry: others are more reflective than analytic, allowing readers to see what it means to live intimately with Scripture. As a unity, the collection presents Ruth and Song of Songs not only as ancient texts that deserve to be treasured but as old worlds capable of begetting the new.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Essays.2bisacsh1 aAschkenasy, Nehama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloch, Chana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrettler, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurrows, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCushing Stahlberg, Lesleigh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavis, Ellen F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFassler, Margot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFontaine, Carole R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkins, Peter S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkins, Peter S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHellerstein, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKates, Judith A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaCocque, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatter, E. Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOsherow, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc